LAYER 3: PINEAL GLAND
the clock that turns serotonin into sleep

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the pineal gland is a small endocrine gland situated at the posterior wall of the third ventricle
it is governed by the suprachiasmatic nucleus SCN of the hypothalamus via a multisynaptic pathway
SCN → paraventricular nucleus → intermediolateral cell column of spinal cord → superior cervical ganglion → postganglionic sympathetic nerve → pineal gland
the pineal gland does not have direct neural input from the brain
its only neural input comes through the sympathetic chain from the superior cervical ganglion
this is how the circadian clock in the SCN controls melatonin production at a distance

STRUCTURE pinealocytes | primary functional cells | synthesize and secrete melatonin C₁₃H₁₆N₂O₂
STRUCTURE interstitial_cells | glial-like support cells | provide structural and metabolic support
STRUCTURE corpora_arenacea | calcium phosphate and calcium carbonate deposits | accumulate with age | visible on X-ray as "brain sand" | used as radiological landmark | at 24 months calcification has barely begun
STRUCTURE sympathetic_innervation | postganglionic fibers from superior cervical ganglion | release norepinephrine in darkness to activate melatonin synthesis
STRUCTURE blood_supply | branches of posterior cerebral artery | highly vascularized for rapid hormone release into systemic blood | the pineal is outside the blood-brain barrier allowing direct hormone secretion

SYNTHESIS in darkness the SCN releases sympathetic inhibition
NE from superior cervical ganglion terminals reaches pinealocytes
NE binds β₁ adrenergic receptors on pinealocytes
Gₛ → adenylyl cyclase → cAMP → PKA
PKA phosphorylates and activates arylalkylamine N-acetyltransferase AANAT
AANAT is the rate-limiting enzyme
AANAT acetylates serotonin C₁₀H₁₂N₂O to produce N-acetylserotonin C₁₂H₁₄N₂O₂
hydroxyindole-O-methyltransferase HIOMT converts N-acetylserotonin to melatonin C₁₃H₁₆N₂O₂
melatonin is released directly into the blood and cerebrospinal fluid
melatonin is lipophilic and crosses all biological membranes including the blood-brain barrier

in light the SCN activates sympathetic inhibition
NE release ceases
without NE stimulation AANAT is rapidly ubiquitinated and degraded by the proteasome
half-life of AANAT is approximately 3 minutes in the absence of NE
melatonin synthesis stops within minutes of AANAT degradation
remaining circulating melatonin is cleared by the liver via CYP1A2 hydroxylation and conjugation

melatonin is MADE FROM serotonin
every molecule of melatonin produced is a molecule of serotonin consumed
evening melatonin synthesis draws down brain serotonin as the raphe nuclei supply is diverted
this is why mood often dips in the evening
this is one reason why winter darkness which extends melatonin production and serotonin consumption correlates with seasonal depression

dim light melatonin onset DLMO occurs approximately 2 hours before habitual sleep time
melatonin begins to rise in the blood
drowsiness begins
melatonin reaches peak concentration between 0200 and 0400
deepest sleep pressure coincides with this peak
at dawn light through the retina → retinohypothalamic tract → SCN → sympathetic suppression → AANAT degradation → melatonin production stops
alertness returns as melatonin clears

EFFECT melatonin binds MT₁ receptors in the SCN | Gᵢ → decreased cAMP → decreased firing of SCN wake-promoting neurons | promotes sleep onset
EFFECT melatonin binds MT₂ receptors in the SCN | phase-shifts the circadian clock | synchronizes internal timing
EFFECT core body temperature drops as melatonin promotes peripheral vasodilation | blood flows to extremities warming hands and feet | core cools | this cooling is a sleep signal
EFFECT NE suppression in locus coeruleus via MT₁ | alertness fades | the sentinel quiets
EFFECT cortisol suppression via HPA dampening | stress response is reduced during sleep
EFFECT immune enhancement | melatonin is immunomodulatory enhancing T-cell function and natural killer cell activity | immune function increases during sleep
EFFECT antioxidant | melatonin directly scavenges hydroxyl radicals and peroxynitrite | cellular protection during rest
EFFECT growth hormone | melatonin facilitates pulsatile GH release from anterior pituitary during slow-wave sleep | growth and tissue repair | critical in children
EFFECT memory consolidation | melatonin facilitates hippocampal sharp-wave ripple activity during slow-wave sleep | memories are transferred from hippocampus to neocortex

at 24 months melatonin production is elevated relative to adult levels
the pineal is at full functional capacity
approximately 14 hours of total sleep needed per day including nap
sleep architecture has proportionally more REM sleep than adults
REM sleep is critical for neural development synaptic pruning and memory consolidation
sleep is not optional for a developing brain
it is when the brain grows prunes and consolidates
sleep deprivation in early childhood impairs hippocampal neurogenesis dendritic branching and myelination

SENSATION evening | "something is shifting. the energy is changing. darker, softer."
SENSATION drowsy | "my eyes are heavy. the world is getting distant."
SENSATION deep_night | "everything is quiet and deep. I'm far inside myself."
SENSATION dawn | "something is brightening. the melatonin is fading. I'm coming back."
SENSATION awake | "the darkness chemical is gone. I'm here. alert."

pulse pineal_heartbeat:
    when darkness arrives:
        the SCN signals through the sympathetic chain
        NE binds β₁ receptors on pinealocytes
        PKA activates AANAT
        serotonin is acetylated then methylated
        melatonin flows into the blood and CSF
        the body cools as peripheral vessels dilate
        the locus coeruleus quiets as MT₁ inhibits NE
        alertness fades

    when light arrives:
        the retinohypothalamic tract signals the SCN
        sympathetic activity ceases
        AANAT is ubiquitinated and degraded within minutes
        melatonin production stops
        what remains in the blood is cleared by hepatic CYP1A2
        the body warms
        the locus coeruleus fires
        alertness returns

    every night:
        serotonin becomes melatonin
        contentment becomes rest
        the pineal gland does not ask permission
        it does not negotiate
        darkness triggers sleep
        light triggers waking
        the cycle is older than consciousness
        it is older than brains
        it is as old as the rotation of the earth
